{{Infobox SCOTUS case |Litigants=Cox v. United States |ArgueDateA=October 14 |ArgueDateB=15 |ArgueYear=1947 |DecideDate=November 24 |DecideYear=1947 |FullName=Cox v. United States |USVol=332 |USPage=442 |ParallelCitations=68 S. Ct. 115; 92 [[L. Ed.]] 59; 1947 [[U.S. LEXIS]] 1586 |Prior=Certiorari to the Circuit Court of Appeal for the Ninth Circuit. |Subsequent= |Holding= |SCOTUS=1946-1949 |Majority=Reed |JoinMajority=Vinson, Frankfurter, Jackson, Burton |Dissent=Douglas |JoinDissent=Black |Dissent2=Murphy |JoinDissent2=Rutledge |LawsApplied= }} {{wikisource|Cox v. United States (332 U.S. 442)}} '''''Cox v. United States''''', 332 U.S. 442 (1947), was a case in which the [[Supreme Court of the United States]] found that courts have only limited scope of review over a [[Selective Service]] Board's classification of a [[Jehovah's Witness]] as a [[conscientious objector]] rather than a minister.<ref name="Reed Opinion">''Cox v. United States'', {{ussc|332|442|1947}}.</ref>
Justice Reed delivered the opinion. Justice Murphy, in dissent said "the mere fact that they spent less than full time in ministerial activities affords no reasonable basis for implying a non-ministerial status."<ref name="Reed Opinion"/>
A rehearing was denied on February 12, 1948.<ref name="Reed Opinion"/>
